description.value: Gold couchant lion: the body cast with a hole through the chest to the tail; the rectangular baseplate with curved front edge was made separately. The body is smooth and undecorated except for details of the mane which are chased between parallel lines, and the feathering on the forelegs. The face is expressive, with large, downturned eyes, an unusual feature. The nose is prominent, the mouth upcurved. The chest is undecorated and covered with a coppery deposit. The tail is made from a piece of wire looped around the right haunch, decorated with short incised lines and ending in a knob. On the base-plate is inscribed, to the right,  a scene showing two dancing men flanking a 'nefer'-sign. The cross-bar of the hieroglyph is lower than usual because of the position of the mens' arms. To the left is a hawk representing Horus, and a Set-animal followed by three hieroglyphs.

description.value: Gold foil recumbent sphinx: bent and damaged. The whole of each side including the pedestal was made in one piece with a punch in a shaped mould - the join is visible down the centre of the nose and the middle of the back. The back of the pedestal on which the sphinx sits is rounded. A base-plate, slightly turned up at the edges, was added to the bottom. Under the chin of the sphinx is a cylindrical tube, slightly corrugated, representing the beard; this in turn rests on another tube, set at right-angles, providing the passage for the stringing and protecting the figure itself from being rubbed by the thread or wire, as did a collar of gold wire at the back of the sphinx where the thread or wire emerged.    The sphinx has a human head and lion's bodies. On its heads it wears the 'nemes' headdress with a uraeus made from wire curving across the top of the head in four loops. The sphinx's tails ismade from wire and arranged around the right haunch; it is thickened into a knob at the end. Signs of solder under the uraeus and joining the tail to the body are visible.
